Better design helps.  Imagine that BatchLabel was an abstract type, then
imagine that it has ten subclasses.  Every test for type BatchLabel would
work for every sub-class.  I&#39;d say that&#39;s pretty efficient.  
Design your test classes to map to your system classes.  That way you can
keep your test classes as managabe as you keep your system classes.

Also, in your example, all the tests are doing the same thing i.e.
instantiating an object then testing that the getBatchLabel method is
functioning properly.  If your tests are doing similar stuff then there will
be a case for a quick re-factor.

And that JUnit fail after one test fails, so what?  You want all tests to
pass so if one fails, find it, fix your code, and go again.

